Niobe, daughter of Tantalus and wife of Amphion, king of Thebes, proud of her six sons and six daughters, declared herself superior to Latona, who had only one son and one daughter. Thereupon Apollo slew all her sons and Diana all her daughters. Dav. notes that Lucian also, de Saltat. ἓ 41, mentions τὴν ἐπὶ τῷ πένθει σι’γήν of Niobe.

propter aeternum: F.A.W. thinks this theory probably due to the Stoic tendency to apply allegory to myths; for this tendency see Zeller, Smin, etc. ‚ c. xiii pp. 346—7.
